<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>
Native Languages of the Americas: Wampanoag<BR>(Massachusett, Natick, Nantucket, Mashpee)
</H1>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><script type="text/javascript"><!--
google_ad_client = "pub-8872632675285158";
/* 728x15 link ad */
google_ad_slot = "7815442998";
google_ad_width = 728;
google_ad_height = 15;
//-->
</script>
<script type="text/javascript"
src="http://pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/show_ads.js">
</script></P>

<B>Language:</b> Wampanoag--also known as Massachusett, Pokanoket, Nantucket, Natick, Massasoit, Nauset, or Mashpee--is an
<A href="http://www.native-languages.org/famalg.htm">Algonkian</a> language of New England.
The language is no longer actively spoken in Wampanoag communities today, although some Wampanoag
people are trying to <A href="http://www.native-languages.org/revive.htm">revive</a> it.  
<A href="http://www.native-languages.org/narragansett.htm">Narragansett</a> is considered by some linguists to have been
a Wampanoag dialect, by others a distinct language.
<BR><BR>

<b><U>Sponsored Links</U></b><BR>
<script type="text/javascript">
    google_ad_client = "ca-pub-8872632675285158";
    google_ad_slot = "7933889216";
    google_ad_width = 336;
    google_ad_height = 280;
</script>
<!-- ATF large bordered ad -->
<script type="text/javascript"
